To configure nginx as a reverse proxy, you need to follow these steps:

1. Install nginx on your server. You can use the package manager of your operating system to install it. For example, on Ubuntu, you can use the following command:
```
sudo apt-get install nginx
```

2. Open the nginx configuration file using a text editor. For example, on Ubuntu, you can use the following command:
```
sudo nano /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
```

3. Add the following configuration to the file:
```
http {
    upstream backend {
        server 127.0.0.1:8080;
    }

    server {
        listen 80;

        location / {
            proxy_pass http://backend;
            proxy_set_header Host $host;
            proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
            proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        }
    }
}
```

4. Save the file and exit the text editor.

5. Restart nginx to apply the changes:
```
sudo systemctl restart nginx
```

Now, nginx is configured as a reverse proxy. You can test it by accessing the URL of your server in a web browser. If everything is set up correctly, you should see the website hosted by the backend server.

